 -> cmnds
    -> fg
        ( foreground )
    -> bg
        ( background ) or ctr+z

    -> jobs
        ( show list pause and running programs in background)

    -> nohup
        ( no hand up )
        -> nohup {command} &
        https://andreyex.ru/operacionnaya-sistema-linux/komanda-nohup-v-linux-pozvolyaet-zapuskat-komandy-dazhe-posle-vyhoda-iz-sistemy/
        https://www.computerhope.com/unix/unohup.htm

    -> ps
        ( info about active processes )
        -> keys:
            -> -a
                ( show all process )
            -> -x
                ( show unbounded terminal process )
            -> -e
                ( show all system process )
            -> -f
                ( show process tree )
            -> -u
                ( show user process )

    -> pstree
        ( process tree )
        http://linux.yaroslavl.ru/docs/setup/mandrake/cl/process-info.html

    -> pgrep
        ( find process )

    -> pkill
        ( kill process )

     -> killall

    -> top
        ( task manager )

    -> free
        ( operative load )

    -> uptime
        ( working time )

    -> screen
        ( manage sessions )

-> daemons
    -> config files for services: /etc/event.d
    -> all scripts in: /etc/init.d
        -> start functions: /lib/lsb/init-functions
    -> symbol links on scripts: /etc/rcX.d (X - run level)

-> run tasks on a schedule:
    -> cron
        -> global conf: /etc/crontab
            -> set example:
               https://1cloud.ru/help/linux/kak-nastroit-planirovshchik-cron-na-crontab-linux
        -> user conf: /var/spool/cron/*

    -> anacron
        https://blog.sedicomm.com/2020/04/11/cron-ili-anacron-kak-planirovat-vypolnenie-zadach-s-pomoshhyu-anacron-v-linux/
        -> etc/anacrontab

    -> at